forms. According to Lia Rumantscha (LR), a Swiss academic institute devoted to promoting Romansh language and culture, one of the biggest difficulties for the future of the language is emigration of native Romansh speakers and lack of available Romansh education for children with another of the country's other official languages (German, French, and Italian) as their first language.%0a%3c %0a%3c Today, Romansh is supported by various government-supported and independent efforts in revitalization. Immigrants to the Graubünden canton can receive a language certificate in Romansh, and LR has developed a specific course for Portuguese immigrants after an influx in recent years. There is also a revitalization of Romansh in the arts; Liricas Analas is a hip hop group that performs exclusively in Romansh. In the 2023–24 school year, LR will be launching a program for Swiss high school students to learn Romansh as an option alongside the other national languages for the "third national language" requirement.%0a%3c %0a%3c Examples of spoken Romansh:%0a%3c • https://youtu.be/LAnWWcSrTFU — Lone speaker%0a%3c • https://youtu.be/n7fJBUH1JCE — Conversational (w/ translated subtitles)%0a%3c %0a%3c Sources:%0a%3c • https://www.bbc.com/travel/article/20180627-switzerlands-mysterious-fourth-language%0a%3c • https://www.ethnologue.com/size-and-vitality/roh%0a%3c • https://unesdoc.unesco.org/ark:/48223/pf0000187026%0a%3c • https://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/politics/romansh_switzerland-s-smallest-national-language-struggles-for-survival/43242444%0a%3c • http://www.liarumantscha.ch/?changeLang=_en%0a%3c • https://migration.swiss/en/migration-report-2021/immigration-and-integration/romansh%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3